<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ai-research-tools">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Stage-to-tool mapping for AI-augmented research pipelines: Haiku for dispatch, Sonnet for synthesis, Opus for validation of critical data.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>research-tools</tag>
      <tag>multi-stage-pipeline</tag>
      <tag>agent-orchestration</tag>
      <tag>source-attribution</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AI Research Tools (geek/researcher)</title>

    <summary>Stage-to-tool mapping for AI-augmented research pipelines with orchestrator pattern: Haiku for dispatch, Sonnet for synthesis, Opus for validation.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>No single AI tool covers all research stages. Tools that try to cover everything produce shallow, biased results and lose source attribution. Matching tool to stage improves citation quality, reduces hallucination risk, and makes the pipeline auditable. 95% of researchers now use AI tools regularly (2025); the key differentiator is task-specific tool assignment, not general-purpose chat.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building or instrumenting a multi-stage research pipeline for a geek/agent project</item>
        <item>Selecting the right tool before starting any structured literature or market sweep</item>
        <item>Producing synthesis reports from heterogeneous sources (news, academic, market data)</item>
        <item>Citation tracking and source verification is required</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Primary source collection requiring human judgment (expert interviews, observation)</item>
        <item>Legally sensitive research where AI hallucination risk is unacceptable</item>
        <item>Real-time data requiring live API access beyond what exposed tools support</item>
        <item>Tasks where source provenance must be court-admissible or regulatory-grade</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="tool-stack-by-stage">
      <p>Assign exactly one primary tool per research stage. Using the same tool across stages hides coverage gaps and degrades source attribution.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Map each research stage to its specialist tool before starting any query.</statement>
        <rationale>Perplexity excels at cited multi-source synthesis; competitor intelligence tools (Crayon, Klue) are optimized for tracking product and pricing changes; interview analysis tools (Looppanel, Dovetail) require pre-uploaded transcripts. A general-purpose chat model cannot substitute any of these at scale.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="stage-map">
        <list>
          <item>Exploration — Perplexity, ChatGPT, Claude</item>
          <item>Deep Research — Perplexity Pro Search, Claude Research Mode</item>
          <item>Competitor Analysis — Crayon, Klue, Kompyte, Contify, AlphaSense</item>
          <item>User Sentiment — Brandwatch, Sprout Social</item>
          <item>Market Data — Statista AI, CB Insights</item>
          <item>Trend Analysis — Exploding Topics, Google Trends</item>
          <item>Interview Analysis — Looppanel, Dovetail, Insight7, UserBit</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="workflow-steps">
      <rule>
        <statement>Execute research stages sequentially: define questions → broad AI exploration → human curation → AI synthesis → human analysis → AI report draft → human finalization.</statement>
        <rationale>A human checkpoint between broad exploration and deep research prevents propagating low-quality seeds downstream. Skipping curation compounds hallucination risk in the synthesis step.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Document which AI tool produced each finding in the final report.</statement>
        <rationale>Reviewers need source attribution to calibrate trust. Hiding AI involvement or omitting tool names prevents reproducibility and trust auditing.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="model-assignment">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use Haiku for mechanical tool invocation and parameter setup; Sonnet for multi-source synthesis; Opus for validating critical data points where hallucination risk is high.</statement>
        <rationale>Model cost scales with complexity. Mechanical dispatch does not require frontier reasoning; synthesis does. Opus is reserved for high-stakes validation, not routine queries.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="orchestrator-pattern">
      <rule>
        <statement>Deploy a Claude Sonnet orchestrator that forms queries, dispatches to tool-specific APIs, receives raw results, then passes to a synthesis step — never combining dispatch and synthesis in one call.</statement>
        <rationale>Chaining dispatch and synthesis in a single call causes the agent to lose track of source attribution. Separate calls allow explicit source metadata to be passed through every step.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Set an iteration budget per stage (e.g., max 3 Perplexity queries for exploration) before the pipeline starts.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a budget, agents spiral into diminishing-return queries, inflating cost and context. A fixed budget forces prioritization and prevents scope creep.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="xml"><![CDATA[
<research_task>
  <question>Top 5 AI-native research tools for market sizing in 2026?</question>
  <sources>perplexity, web-search</sources>
  <output_format>JSON: tool, use_case, pricing, agent_api_available</output_format>
  <verify>cross-reference at least 2 sources per tool claim</verify>
</research_task>
        ]]></code>
        <note>Declares sources explicitly and requires cross-referencing. Prevents single-source hallucination.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="xml"><![CDATA[
<synthesis_task>
  <raw_findings>{{findings_json}}</raw_findings>
  <instruction>Identify contradictions. Flag any claim supported by fewer than 2 sources.
  Output structured markdown report.</instruction>
</synthesis_task>
        ]]></code>
        <note>Synthesis step receives raw JSON from dispatch step. Source metadata travels through explicitly.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule>
        <statement>Verify AI findings against primary sources before including in deliverables.</statement>
        <rationale>95% of researchers use AI tools regularly (2025), but citation quality varies: Perplexity cites URLs, Claude/ChatGPT can hallucinate references. Primary-source verification is the mandatory last step.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Assign tool to stage, not to question: use Perplexity for exploration, AlphaSense for industry filings, Dovetail for interview synthesis</item>
        <item>Document which AI tool produced each claim in the final report; reviewers need this for trust calibration</item>
        <item>Run top-down and bottom-up research paths independently before merging, to avoid anchoring bias from first result</item>
        <item>Set iteration budgets per stage (e.g., max 3 Perplexity queries for exploration) to control cost and scope creep</item>
        <item>Verify any statistic cited by an AI tool against the linked primary source before including in deliverables</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using one general-purpose chat model for all research stages.</description>
        <reason>Interview-analysis, competitor-intel, and market-data stages each require specialist tooling; a single LLM cannot substitute all three and produces shallow, biased, citation-poor results.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Trusting AI output without human analysis.</description>
        <reason>The era of "best AI assistant" as a single winner is over (2026). The right assistant is task-matched; no tool triangulates all stages autonomously — human curation between stages is mandatory.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Perplexity API results differ from the web UI (no "Pro Search" toggle in API v1; use search_recency_filter instead).</description>
        <reason>Testing only the web UI and then relying on the API will produce coverage gaps; both must be validated before committing to API-only flow.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Synthesis agents lose track of source attribution when chaining multiple tool calls without explicit metadata passthrough.</description>
        <reason>Source metadata must be passed explicitly through every pipeline step, or the final report cannot be audited for citation quality.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Free-tier rate limits (Google Trends, SerpAPI) silently truncate results without error.</description>
        <reason>Truncated results look complete but are not; add explicit error handling and result-count validation for every rate-limited tool.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Deploy a Claude subagent as an orchestrator that runs stages sequentially: it forms queries, invokes web-search or Perplexity API, receives raw results, and hands off to a synthesis step. Use Haiku for mechanical query-dispatch and Sonnet for multi-source synthesis. Opus is reserved for validation of critical data points where hallucination risk is high. A human checkpoint between "broad exploration" and "deep research" prevents propagating low-quality seeds downstream.</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent (drives structured research tasks defined in SDD specs), nero-sdd-executor-agent (same pattern, NERO-side orchestration).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>perplexity-cli (unofficial): Query Perplexity API from shell (pip install perplexity-python / docs.perplexity.ai)</item>
        <item>claude (Anthropic CLI): Drive Claude for synthesis (pip install anthropic / docs.anthropic.com/en/api)</item>
        <item>serpapi: Google/Bing structured results (pip install google-search-results / serpapi.com)</item>
        <item>exploding-topics-api: Trend signal extraction (REST API, explodingtopics.com/api)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>Perplexity Pro (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Yes REST API): Best for cited multi-source synthesis</item>
        <item>AlphaSense (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Partial export-only): Strong for SEC filings, earnings calls</item>
        <item>Crayon (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Partial webhook triggers): Competitive intel; no natural-language query API</item>
        <item>Brandwatch (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Partial REST API): Social sentiment; complex auth setup</item>
        <item>Statista (SaaS, Agent-friendly: No): Data download only; agent must parse PDFs</item>
        <item>Google Trends (Free, Agent-friendly: Yes pytrends library): Rate-limited; useful for trend signals</item>
        <item>Dovetail (SaaS, Agent-friendly: Partial CSV export): Requires human-uploaded transcripts</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/research-dispatch.py" purpose="Claude SDK dispatcher for multi-source synthesis"/>
      <template path="templates/research-prompt.txt" purpose="XML prompt template for research and synthesis tasks"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
